{{Short description|1460 year calendar cycle of ancient Egypt}} [[File:Hubble heic0206j.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Sirius (star)|Sirius]] (''bottom'') and [[Orion (constellation)|Orion]] (''right''). The [[Winter Triangle]] is formed from the three brightest stars in the northern winter sky: Sirius, [[:en:Betelgeuse|Betelgeuse]] (''top right''), and [[Procyon]] (''top left'').]] [[File:CanisMajorCC.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Sirius as the brightest star in the [[:en:Asterism (astronomy)|constellation]] [[:en:Canis Major|Canis Major]] as observed from the Earth (lines added for clarity).]] The '''Sothic cycle''' or '''Canicular period''' is a period of 1,461&nbsp;[[:en:Egyptian civil year|Egyptian civil year]]s of 365&nbsp;days each or 1,460&nbsp;[[:en:Julian calendar|Julian years]] averaging {{frac|365|1|4}}&nbsp;days each. During a Sothic cycle, the 365-day year loses enough time that the start of its year once again coincides with the [[heliacal rising]] of the star [[Sirius]] ({{langx|egy|}} or {{lang|egy-Latn|[[Sopdet]]}}, 'Triangle'; {{langx|grc|Σῶθις}}, {{lang|Grc-Latn|Sō̂this}}) on 19&nbsp;July in the [[:en:Julian calendar|Julian calendar]].<ref name=lavia>{{citation |contribution-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225071503/https://www.lavia.org/english/archivo/egyptiancalendaren.html |contribution=Ancient Egyptian Civil Calendar |title=La Via |url=http://www.lavia.org/indexIT.html |access-date=8 February 2017 }}.</ref>{{efn|The date slowly varies within the [[:en:Gregorian calendar|Gregorian calendar]], moving about three days later every four centuries. It presently occurs around the beginning of August.}} It is an important aspect of [[:en:Egyptology|Egyptology]], particularly with regard to reconstructions of the [[:en:Egyptian calendar|Egyptian calendar]] and its history. [[:en:Egyptian astronomy|Astronomical records]] of this displacement may have been responsible for the later establishment of the more accurate [[:en:Julian calendar|Julian]] and [[:en:Alexandrian calendar|Alexandrian calendar]]s.
==Mechanics== The [[:en:Ancient Egypt|Ancient Egypt]]ian [[:en:Egyptian calendar|civil year]], its holidays, and religious records reflect its apparent establishment at a point when the [[heliacal rising|return]] of the bright star [[Sirius (star)|Sirius]] to the night sky was considered to herald the annual [[:en:Flooding of the Nile|Flooding of the Nile]].<ref name=teacosy/> However, because the civil calendar was exactly 365&nbsp;days long and did not incorporate [[:en:Leap year|Leap year]]s until 22&nbsp;BCE, its months "wandered" backwards through the [[solar year]] at the rate of about one day in every four years. This almost exactly corresponded to its displacement against the '''Sothic&nbsp;year''' as well. (The Sothic year is about a minute longer than a [[:en:Julian year (calendar)|Julian year]].)<ref name=teacosy>{{harvp|Tetley|2014|p=[http://www.egyptchronology.com/uploads/2/6/9/4/26943741/ch_3_investigating_ancient_egyptian_calendars.pdf 42]}}.</ref> The [[sidereal year]] of 365.25636&nbsp;days is valid only for stars on the [[:en:Ecliptic|Ecliptic]] (the apparent path of the [[Sun]] across the sky) and having no [[proper motion]], whereas Sirius's displacement ~40° below the ecliptic, its proper motion, and the wobbling of the [[:en:celestial equator|celestial equator]] cause the period between its [[heliacal rising]]s to be almost exactly 365.25&nbsp;days long instead. This steady loss of one relative day every four years over the course of the 365-day calendar meant that the "wandering" day would return to its original place relative to the solar and Sothic year after precisely 1461&nbsp;Egyptian civil years or 1460&nbsp;Julian years.<ref name=lavia/>
==Discovery== This calendar cycle was well known in antiquity. Censorinus described it in his book ''De Die Natale'', in CE 238, and stated that the cycle had renewed 100 years earlier on the 12th of August. In the ninth century, Syncellus epitomized the Sothic Cycle in the "Old Egyptian Chronicle." Isaac Cullimore, an early Egyptologist and member of the Royal Society, published a discourse on it in 1833 in which he was the first to suggest that Censorinus had fudged the terminus date, and that it was more likely to fall in CE 136. He also computed the likely date of its invention as being around 1600 BCE.
In 1904, seven decades after Cullimore, [[:en:Eduard Meyer|Eduard Meyer]] carefully combed known Egyptian inscriptions and written materials to find any mention of the calendar dates when Sirius rose at dawn. He found six of them, on which the dates of much of conventional [[:en:Egyptian chronology|Egyptian chronology]] are based. A heliacal rise of Sirius was recorded by [[:en:Censorinus|Censorinus]] as having happened on the Egyptian New Year's Day between 139&nbsp;CE and 142&nbsp;CE.<ref name=Kitchen>{{cite journal |last=Kitchen |first=K.A. |date=October 1991 |title=The chronology of Ancient Egypt |journal=World Archaeology |volume=23 |number=2 |page=205|doi=10.1080/00438243.1991.9980172 }}</ref>
The record itself actually refers to 21&nbsp;July 140&nbsp;CE, but astronomical calculation definitely dates the heliacal rising at 20&nbsp;July 139&nbsp;CE, Julian. This correlates the Egyptian calendar to the [[:en:Julian calendar|Julian calendar]]. A Julian leap day occurs in 140&nbsp;CE, and so the new year on 1&nbsp;[[Thoth (month)|Thoth]] is 20&nbsp;July in 139&nbsp;CE but it is 19&nbsp;July for 140–142&nbsp;CE. Thus [[:en:Eduard Meyer|Meyer]] was able to compare the Egyptian civil calendar date on which Sirius was observed rising heliacally to the Julian calendar date on which Sirius ''ought'' to have risen, count the number of intercalary days needed, and determine how many years were between the beginning of a cycle and the observation.
To calculate a date astronomically, one also needs to know the place of observation, since the latitude of the observation changes the day when the heliacal rising of Sirius can be seen, and mislocating an observation can potentially throw off the resulting chronology by several decades.<ref name=Kitchen/> Official observations are known to have been made at [[:en:Heliopolis (Ancient Egypt)|Heliopolis]] (or [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]], near [[:en:Cairo|Cairo]]), [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]], and [[:en:Elephantine|Elephantine]] (near [[:en:Aswan|Aswan]]),<ref name=teatime/> with the rising of Sirius observed at Cairo about 8&nbsp;days after it is seen at Aswan.<ref name=teatime>{{cite book |last=Tetley |first=M. Christine |year=2014 |title=The Reconstructed Chronology of the Egyptian Kings |volume=I |url=http://www.egyptchronology.com/vols-1--2.html |page=[http://www.egyptchronology.com/uploads/2/6/9/4/26943741/ch_3_investigating_ancient_egyptian_calendars.pdf 43] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211075421/http://www.egyptchronology.com/vols-1--2.html |archive-date=2017-02-11}}</ref>
Meyer concluded that the Egyptian civil calendar was created in [[:en:5th millennium BC|4241&nbsp;BCE]].<ref name=Meyer>[https://archive.org/details/aegyptischechron00meye/page/41/mode/1up?view=theater Meyer, Eduard, ''Aegyptische Chronologie'', Berlin, Verlag der Königliche Akadamie der Wissenschaften (1904), Ch. I, p.41]</ref><ref name=Breasted>[https://archive.org/details/historyoftheanci034958mbp/page/15/mode/1up?view=theater Breasted, James Henry, ''A History of the Ancient Egyptians'', New York, Charles Scribner's Sons (1908), Ch. II, p.15] ("[T]he calendar year of 365 days was introduced in 4241 B.C., the earliest fixed date in the history of the world as known to us."), citing Meyer.</ref> Recent scholarship, however, has discredited that claim. Most scholars either move the observation upon which he based this forward by one cycle of Sirius, to 19&nbsp;July 2781&nbsp;BCE, or reject the assumption that the document on which Meyer relied indicates a rise of Sirius at all.<ref name=Grimal-1988>{{cite book |last=Grimal |first=Nicolas |year=1988 |title=A History of Ancient Egypt |publisher=Librairie Arthéme Fayard}}</ref>{{rp|page=52}}
